To delete files you’ve already uploaded to GitHub, the steps depend on whether you want to remove them from:

The latest version of your repository

The entire Git history (permanently)

I’ll walk you through both.

✅ Option 1: Delete a File from the Repository (Simple Method – Web UI)

If you just want to remove the file from the current version:

Go to your repository on GitHub

Navigate to the file you want to delete

Click the file

Click the 🗑 Delete this file button (top right)

Add a commit message

Click Commit changes

Done ✅

The file will be removed from the latest version but still exists in previous commits.

✅ Option 2: Delete a File Using Git (Command Line)

If you're working locally:

git rm filename.ext
git commit -m "Delete unwanted file"
git push origin main


If you're using another branch, replace main with your branch name.

🚨 Option 3: Completely Remove a File from Git History (Sensitive Data)

If you accidentally uploaded:

Passwords

API keys

Large files

Private data

You must rewrite history.

Recommended Tool: git filter-repo (modern method)
git filter-repo --path filename.ext --invert-paths
git push origin --force


⚠️ Warning:

This rewrites history.

Anyone who cloned the repo must re-clone it.

Force push is required.

💡 If It’s a Large File

If GitHub rejected your push due to file size:

Remove it with git rm

Consider using Git LFS

Or remove from history using filter-repo

